WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.840
[Unknown]: I.V.M.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.560
[Amit Varma]: literature do a fantastic job of illuminating and illustrating the human condition.

00:00:34.560 --> 00:00:36.080
[Amit Varma]: So who needs philosophy?

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:38.920
[Amit Varma]: And hey, is that itself a philosophical question?

00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:41.000
[Amit Varma]: If so, do we need to answer it?

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:48.600
[Unknown]: Welcome to the Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:49.600
[Unknown]: science.

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:53.320
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:54.760
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the Scene and the Unseen.

00:00:54.760 --> 00:00:58.960
[Amit Varma]: The philosopher Alfred North Whitehead once said that all of Western philosophy was nothing

00:00:58.960 --> 00:01:02.440
[Amit Varma]: more than a series of footnotes to Plato.

00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:04.120
[Amit Varma]: From this, you can gather two things.

00:01:04.120 --> 00:01:09.040
[Amit Varma]: One, unlike other fields, philosophy does not seem to have made that much progress in

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:10.320
[Amit Varma]: the last 2000 years.

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:12.480
[Amit Varma]: I would argue, though, that this is not quite true.

00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:16.640
[Amit Varma]: The second thing that quotation tells you is that Plato was a rock star.

00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:21.040
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, while reading Rebecca Goldstein's superb book, Plato at the Googleplex, Why

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:26.240
[Amit Varma]: Philosophy Won't Go Away, I was struck by what a foundational thinker Plato really was.

00:01:26.240 --> 00:01:31.320
[Amit Varma]: He asked many big questions that still drive philosophical inquiry today, and he anticipated

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:34.920
[Amit Varma]: insights that were given proper shape many centuries later.

00:01:34.920 --> 00:01:39.360
[Amit Varma]: For example, we think of the social contract as a concept that was formulated during the

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:40.400
[Amit Varma]: Enlightenment.

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:44.460
[Amit Varma]: And the field of game theory is something that came about in the 20th century.

00:01:44.460 --> 00:01:49.440
[Amit Varma]: So my eyes almost popped out of my head when I read a dialogue of Plato in which Glaucon,

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:54.200
[Amit Varma]: elder brother of Plato and a minor character in this dialogue, describes what is basically

00:01:54.200 --> 00:01:58.000
[Amit Varma]: a game theoretic argument for a social contract.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:02.160
[Amit Varma]: And Plato's dialogues, as I discovered in Goldstein's excellent book, are full of such

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:05.440
[Amit Varma]: seemingly modern arguments and insights.

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:08.920
[Amit Varma]: Plato at the Googleplex is a book that really has two intersecting parts.

00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:13.880
[Amit Varma]: Half the book is a series of illuminating essays on Plato, his times, his philosophy,

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:15.320
[Amit Varma]: the impact of his work.

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:20.500
[Amit Varma]: The other half is a series of fictionalized dialogues of Plato set in current times and

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:25.000
[Amit Varma]: modern venues like the Googleplex, and these are quite witty and entertaining.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.980
[Amit Varma]: Besides introducing us to Plato, the book really makes an argument that philosophy is

00:02:28.980 --> 00:02:34.560
[Amit Varma]: not an arcane academic discipline, but that it actually matters in this modern world,

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:37.400
[Amit Varma]: in these crazy times that we live in.

00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:41.920
[Amit Varma]: I spoke to Goldstein in December 2018 when she was in Mumbai for the Times Lit Fest.

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:46.440
