[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:17.360
[Amit Varma]: It's kind of intimidating to actually have a dialogue with a woman who's written Plato's

00:04:17.360 --> 00:04:20.960
[Amit Varma]: dialogues as you have in your recent book.

00:04:20.960 --> 00:04:26.480
[Amit Varma]: I wanted to start by talking about what the philosopher Carl Jaspers calls the axial age,

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:32.400
[Amit Varma]: which is where you point out in your book that between 800 BC to 200 BC, there was a

00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:38.800
[Amit Varma]: sudden explosion of different quests to find answers to the question of what makes a life

00:04:38.800 --> 00:04:39.960
[Amit Varma]: matter.

00:04:39.960 --> 00:04:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And it showed up in all the different normative religions, the monotheisms that sprang up

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.000
[Amit Varma]: and in philosophy in Greece.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:51.640
[Amit Varma]: But my sort of question was why during this particular period was there this sudden quest?

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:52.640
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:59.440
[Guest]: So when I approached this question of why the ancient Greeks had this massive explosion

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:05.400
[Guest]: of creative ideas, you know, and they're credited with laying down the foundations of Western

00:05:05.400 --> 00:05:10.240
[Guest]: civilization, you know what, it occurred to me that this didn't happen in a vacuum, that

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:14.320
[Guest]: this was happening, you know, in many places on the globe.

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:22.200
[Guest]: And that all of the normative paradigms, you know, meaning the paradigms that people refer

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:27.840
[Guest]: to when they're trying to give meaning and purpose to their lives, whether it's religious

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:31.720
[Guest]: or secular, were formulated during this period.

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:38.400
[Guest]: It was actually a philosopher, a German philosopher of the 20th century named Jaspers.

00:05:38.400 --> 00:05:44.400
[Guest]: He was the first to notice and to name the Axial Age, that there was this great creative

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:49.040
[Guest]: normative ferment during this period.

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:52.960
[Guest]: And so the question is, you know, why did it happen then?

00:05:52.960 --> 00:05:56.600
[Guest]: And social scientists are just beginning to look at this.

00:05:56.600 --> 00:05:59.480
[Guest]: There hasn't been a great deal of attention given to it.

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:04.600
[Guest]: I mean, after all, it was one of those things that was pointed out by philosophers, that

00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:08.440
[Guest]: something amazing was going on during this period.

00:06:08.440 --> 00:06:18.280
[Guest]: It seems like the most important variable was that, simply, the people were well-fed.

00:06:18.280 --> 00:06:26.880
[Guest]: Pascal Boyard in France has plotted the caloric intake all over the globe at that time.

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:33.880
[Guest]: And indeed, the countries that participated in what we call the Axial Age, which was India,

00:06:33.880 --> 00:06:38.720
[Guest]: in Hinduism and Buddhism and Jainism, were formulated during this period.

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:45.880
[Guest]: China, Confucianism and Daoism were formulated during this period, and Greece, philosophy

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:54.640
[Guest]: and tragic poetry, which was their response to this, to these questions of what it is

00:06:54.640 --> 00:06:57.160
[Guest]: that gives meaning and purpose to our lives.

00:06:57.160 --> 00:07:02.160
[Guest]: These were all, and also the Judean hills, you know, where the Abrahamic approach was

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:03.160
[Guest]: formulated.

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:08.960
[Guest]: Persia, Zoroastrianism, all of these places that participated and forged these frameworks

00:07:08.960 --> 00:07:14.040
[Guest]: that are still extant today, claiming all of us in one way or the other, including someone

00:07:14.040 --> 00:07:20.400
[Guest]: like me, who's a secularist, you know, and so I trace my roots back to ancient Greece.

00:07:20.400 --> 00:07:22.520
[Guest]: They were all well-fed.

00:07:22.520 --> 00:07:25.840
[Amit Varma]: And what we learn from this is… Because of the shift to agriculture around

00:07:25.840 --> 00:07:28.200
[Guest]: the 1000 BC. Exactly, exactly right.

00:07:28.200 --> 00:07:33.000
[Guest]: And so, you know, what we learn from this is, you know, when people don't have to be

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:41.480
[Guest]: preoccupied 24-7 and seeing another dawn and, you know, just getting enough food in their

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:48.280
[Guest]: bellies, they start thinking about this question of, you know, here I am and, you know, and

00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:54.040
[Guest]: what is it that I ought to be doing with my life, you know, and so any of these questions

00:07:54.040 --> 00:07:58.320
[Guest]: have that word ought in them, we call normative in philosophy.

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:06.040
[Guest]: And it comes very naturally to our species as soon as we're freed from the, you know,

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:13.120
[Guest]: the constant trials of simply surviving.

00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:18.320
[Guest]: These other features of the… You also pointed out that it correlates with

00:08:18.320 --> 00:08:20.880
[Guest]: urbanization. Exactly.

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:28.800
[Guest]: These were highly organized city-states and they had standing armies, they had coinage,

00:08:28.800 --> 00:08:33.520
[Guest]: they had slavery, they had trading, you know, this is so important, right?

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:38.840
[Guest]: So they were mixing with different people, different cultures, different ways of thinking,

00:08:38.840 --> 00:08:44.360
[Guest]: which makes us humans think, well, what's the right way of thinking about our lives,

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:45.360
[Guest]: right?

00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:50.440
[Guest]: Here are these different traditions, different goals, what's the right way?

00:08:50.440 --> 00:08:54.600
[Guest]: It comes quite naturally to us.

00:08:54.600 --> 00:09:00.120
[Guest]: And also in these cities, there was more anonymity.

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:03.760
[Guest]: I had the great privilege, I don't think I wrote about it in the book because I don't

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:11.000
[Guest]: think I'd had yet this experience, of visiting one of the last of the hunter-gatherer tribes,

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:14.720
[Guest]: of spending a little time with them in Tanzania, the Hadza.

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:17.520
[Guest]: And it was very interesting.

00:09:17.520 --> 00:09:22.400
[Guest]: First of all, they have to really, every day they wake up and they have to fulfill their

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:23.400
[Guest]: caloric needs.

00:09:23.400 --> 00:09:26.720
[Guest]: I mean, and it's very difficult.

00:09:26.720 --> 00:09:31.760
[Guest]: But one of the things that was very clear is they lived in great intimacy with each

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:32.760
[Guest]: other.

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:35.960
[Guest]: Everybody clearly mattered in that village, right?

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:38.000
[Guest]: It's sort of a, it's a family.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:43.520
[Guest]: It's how, this is what we have come from, of intimate village life.

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:49.880
[Guest]: And when, in these big city states and there's more anonymity, this question also I think

00:09:49.880 --> 00:09:50.880
[Guest]: is exacerbated.

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:53.760
[Guest]: Well, you know, who am I?

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:58.700
[Guest]: What can I do to achieve some sense of mattering in the universe?

00:09:58.700 --> 00:10:00.400
[Guest]: In the village life, you matter.

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:03.160
[Guest]: You know, it's, everybody has their position.

00:10:03.160 --> 00:10:05.120
[Guest]: So all of these things come together.

00:10:05.120 --> 00:10:09.240
[Guest]: I don't think it's just a matter of caloric intake.

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:15.000
[Guest]: I think it's more complicated than that, but we see it in all of these places.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.360
[Guest]: There was also a scribe class.

00:10:17.360 --> 00:10:20.680
[Guest]: So there was written language in all, you know, there was written.

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:23.480
[Amit Varma]: And there was coinage, like you've pointed out in your book, so.

00:10:23.480 --> 00:10:25.960
[Guest]: Yes, there was coinage, exactly.

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:32.600
[Guest]: Which is a way of also increasing the sense of sort of anonymity.

00:10:32.600 --> 00:10:37.040
[Guest]: When there's coinage, then there's disparities of wealth, but you know, we all have this

00:10:37.040 --> 00:10:43.480
[Guest]: existential need, even the poor among us, right, of wanting our lives to mean something.

00:10:43.480 --> 00:10:45.680
[Guest]: They mean everything to us.

00:10:45.680 --> 00:10:51.240
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing about this Axial Age is that most, except one, most of the

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:54.740
[Amit Varma]: sort of normative traditions that were forming were teleological.

00:10:54.740 --> 00:10:59.080
[Amit Varma]: You know, they were, they had a god at their center or gods or whatever.

00:10:59.080 --> 00:11:03.480
[Amit Varma]: And the only exception really was the birth of philosophy in ancient Greece.

00:11:03.480 --> 00:11:04.480
[Guest]: Yes.

00:11:04.480 --> 00:11:06.640
[Amit Varma]: And is it because their gods were very messed up?

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:07.640
[Guest]: That's what I think.

00:11:07.640 --> 00:11:18.000
[Guest]: Their gods were really, I'm thinking of, I mean, they were, they're kind of assholes.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Can I say that?

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:20.000
[Unknown]: Yeah, of course.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:21.000
[Unknown]: That's what they really were, right.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:26.760
[Guest]: And it was, it was extremely interesting, you know, we think of the Greeks as, you know,

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:27.760
[Guest]: philosophers.

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:29.680
[Guest]: Of course they weren't philosophers.

00:11:29.680 --> 00:11:31.480
[Guest]: They were not a society of philosophers.

00:11:31.480 --> 00:11:33.160
[Guest]: There's never been a society of philosophers.

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:39.720
[Guest]: They gave, you know, certain among them were philosophers and they gave birth to this way

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:41.920
[Guest]: of approaching the normative questions.

00:11:41.920 --> 00:11:47.360
[Guest]: But we can never forget that it was the Athenian society, which is the best of the Greek city

00:11:47.360 --> 00:11:50.480
[Guest]: states, right, that put Socrates to death.

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:55.080
[Guest]: I mean, there was a democracy that voted, his fellow citizens voted to put him to death.

00:11:55.080 --> 00:11:59.280
[Guest]: So this was not a society of, they regretted it afterwards, right.

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:04.440
[Guest]: But after his death, we find many little statues of Socrates, they regretted it.

00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:09.840
[Guest]: But because of certain things that had happened after they lost the Peloponnesian War, their

00:12:09.840 --> 00:12:17.520
[Guest]: war with another city state, Sparta, they didn't have tolerance for Socrates with his

00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:23.240
[Guest]: skeptical questions anymore, asking them or demanding that they question their own normative

00:12:23.240 --> 00:12:28.480
[Guest]: values, which were not philosophical, but rather something that I call the ethos of

00:12:28.480 --> 00:12:36.040
[Guest]: the extraordinary, that what they had produced was this view that in order to really matter,

00:12:36.040 --> 00:12:42.080
[Guest]: you have to make a name for yourself so that knowledge of your life will be replicated

00:12:42.080 --> 00:12:45.360
[Guest]: in future generations or in your contemporaries.

00:12:45.360 --> 00:12:51.120
[Guest]: And this gives a certain moreness to your life, you know, so fame and glory, what they

00:12:51.120 --> 00:12:53.000
[Guest]: call kleos.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.240
[Guest]: And so that this was, this was their way of pursuing it.

00:12:56.240 --> 00:13:03.320
[Guest]: Any way that you could be replicated in the minds of others, would make your life worth

00:13:03.320 --> 00:13:04.320
[Guest]: living.

00:13:04.320 --> 00:13:07.040
[Guest]: And he was attacking that, Socrates.

00:13:07.040 --> 00:13:11.880
[Amit Varma]: And I found it very interesting how you point out that because their gods are such assholes,

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:16.520
[Amit Varma]: unlike other peoples elsewhere, you don't want the attention of your god, instead, you

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:22.000
[Amit Varma]: want to raise your own renown, like kleos, one way of translating, which I found very

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:27.600
[Amit Varma]: nice, acoustic renown is how you mentioned it's read more people hear of you.

00:13:27.600 --> 00:13:32.160
[Amit Varma]: So they aspire to this ethos of the extraordinary, where they want to do extraordinary things

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:34.960
[Amit Varma]: so that in their own society, they are famous.

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:38.240
[Amit Varma]: Kleos kind of sounds like very Instagram, Twitter, kind of.

00:13:38.240 --> 00:13:39.240
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:13:39.240 --> 00:13:45.000
[Guest]: And it's interesting because, you know, in some sense, we are post-theistic society,

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:46.000
[Guest]: right?

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:53.120
[Guest]: And the more educated we are, the more we don't think of our lives in terms of theism.

00:13:53.120 --> 00:14:02.080
[Guest]: But what we seem to have gone back to follow the default is the pre philosophical Athenian

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:05.000
[Guest]: of you, which is to be replicated in the minds of others.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:10.440
[Guest]: What's extremely interesting, I'm writing about this in my new book, but you know that

00:14:10.440 --> 00:14:18.640
[Guest]: we are, we're a species that really looks for attention one way or the other, right?

00:14:18.640 --> 00:14:23.400
[Guest]: That this is, and in fact, even the way we've evolved, we can, we have, you know, neuroscientists

00:14:23.400 --> 00:14:31.120
[Guest]: have now shown us that we have special areas of the brain, special neurons that are devoted

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:35.480
[Guest]: to being able to see when people are looking directly at us, those neurons will fire.

00:14:35.480 --> 00:14:41.480
[Guest]: If people's eyes are directly on us, a few inches, a few centimeters, either way, other

00:14:41.480 --> 00:14:42.480
[Guest]: neurons will fire.

00:14:42.480 --> 00:14:49.160
[Guest]: So we have this detection system, right, of when people are paying attention to us.

00:14:49.160 --> 00:14:54.520
[Guest]: And I, you know, I've had experience with little babies, my own, and other little babies

00:14:54.520 --> 00:14:59.640
[Guest]: at such an early age, they are making eye contact, extreme eye contact.

00:14:59.640 --> 00:15:05.720
[Guest]: We're so dependent, we're a gregarious species, we're very, very dependent on the care of

00:15:05.720 --> 00:15:10.680
[Guest]: others for a very long time, we have a very long childhood and adolescence, it gets longer

00:15:10.680 --> 00:15:16.480
[Guest]: and longer, I know 45-year-olds now who are still adolescents, but that's another story.

00:15:16.480 --> 00:15:25.200
[Guest]: But so this dependence on our own kind makes us very susceptible to attention.

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:32.040
[Guest]: So what we see in the Axial Age with these gods that most of, you know, how do we want

00:15:32.040 --> 00:15:37.800
[Guest]: to feel that we matter, it's put in terms of, you know, sort of the gods, but the Greeks

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:45.040
[Guest]: were very special because the way that their stories of their gods develop, you don't want

00:15:45.040 --> 00:15:47.360
[Guest]: too much attention from these gods.

00:15:47.360 --> 00:15:51.360
[Guest]: Something bad always happens when a god pays too much attention to you.

00:15:51.360 --> 00:15:56.840
[Guest]: So you want to be glorious, but not so glorious so that the gods feel that you're competition.

00:15:56.840 --> 00:16:01.920
[Guest]: I think of them because I have older brothers and sisters, you know, that the Greek gods

00:16:01.920 --> 00:16:05.720
[Guest]: are sort of like older brothers and sisters, you know, they want you to emulate them and

00:16:05.720 --> 00:16:11.120
[Guest]: to revere them, but then if you start to surpass them, they're going to slap you back into

00:16:11.120 --> 00:16:13.120
[Guest]: your place very, very quickly.

00:16:13.120 --> 00:16:21.440
[Guest]: So it's, the Greek gods are something like this, so they develop this kind of, it was

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:27.440
[Guest]: a highly religious society, saturated with religious rituals, but those were mostly to

00:16:27.440 --> 00:16:33.520
[Guest]: appease the gods, you know, to their apotropaic, that is warding off evil.

00:16:33.520 --> 00:16:37.960
[Guest]: You don't, you know, so don't pay too much attention and I'm paying proper respect to

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:38.960
[Guest]: you.

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:43.080
[Guest]: But in terms of what they wanted, the attention that they wanted to make them feel like they

00:16:43.080 --> 00:16:46.840
[Guest]: matter was from fellow citizens and from future generations.

00:16:46.840 --> 00:16:52.720
[Guest]: So do something big so that the poets will sing of you, which was their social media

00:16:52.720 --> 00:16:53.720
[Amit Varma]: of the day, the poets.

00:16:53.720 --> 00:16:58.960
[Amit Varma]: And sort of the fascinating turning point, which is also at the heart of your book Plato

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:03.600
[Amit Varma]: at the Googleplex, is when from kleos we come to the concept of areta.

00:17:03.600 --> 00:17:05.320
[Guest]: Yes, yes.

00:17:05.320 --> 00:17:13.200
[Guest]: So areta is, you know, what excellence, our word aristocracy, you know, comes from this

00:17:13.200 --> 00:17:14.800
[Guest]: world, the rule of the excellent.

00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:19.120
[Amit Varma]: Benjamin Javid translated it as virtue, but as you pointed out, that doesn't capture

00:17:19.120 --> 00:17:20.120
[Amit Varma]: all its favors.

00:17:20.120 --> 00:17:21.120
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:17:21.120 --> 00:17:24.560
[Guest]: So it originally had meant this, you know, sort of excellence.

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:31.040
[Guest]: You could talk about the areta of a knife or of a horse, you know, so it was the excellence

00:17:31.040 --> 00:17:34.000
[Guest]: of this thing in ancient Greek.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:45.600
[Guest]: And it's really the influence of the philosophers, of Socrates and of Plato, how it comes to

00:17:45.600 --> 00:17:54.920
[Guest]: mean virtue rather than any kind of excellence, because part of the attack of the philosophers

00:17:54.920 --> 00:18:03.880
[Guest]: on the normative framework of their society, why Socrates was put to death, was that the

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:09.520
[Guest]: claim is, you know, not just any kind of kleos will do the trick.

00:18:09.520 --> 00:18:17.160
[Guest]: It has to be areta, it has to be true excellence, and what they argue for is that true excellence

00:18:17.160 --> 00:18:25.640
[Guest]: consists in knowledge, wisdom, virtue, justice, courage, you know, the virtues.

00:18:25.640 --> 00:18:30.280
[Guest]: So the term undergoes this transformation.

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:36.680
[Guest]: And you know, by the time we get to the Gospels, you know, written in Greek, areta simply means,

00:18:36.680 --> 00:18:37.760
[Guest]: you know, virtue.

00:18:37.760 --> 00:18:39.920
[Guest]: It just means virtue.

00:18:39.920 --> 00:18:45.880
[Guest]: This is the transformation that these philosophers who are writing, well not Socrates, he didn't

00:18:45.880 --> 00:18:52.120
[Guest]: write, but Plato, Aristotle, and the philosophers who follow them, that this was a transformation

00:18:52.120 --> 00:18:53.120
[Amit Varma]: of the word.

00:18:53.120 --> 00:18:58.600
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you point out how, you know, Plato's Socrates sort of begins to take areta away

00:18:58.600 --> 00:19:04.960
[Amit Varma]: from kleos or the recognition and sort of shows that it can exist independent of recognition

00:19:04.960 --> 00:19:09.120
[Amit Varma]: that you can be virtuous even if no one else sees your virtue.

00:19:09.120 --> 00:19:15.560
[Amit Varma]: And I want to quote a great, a very nice passage that kind of illustrates that from your book.

00:19:15.560 --> 00:19:20.560
[Amit Varma]: Start quote, in the Gorgias, is that the right way to pronounce it?

00:19:20.560 --> 00:19:25.800
[Amit Varma]: In the Gorgias, Socrates is presented as asserting something so radical that his hearers think

00:19:25.800 --> 00:19:27.280
[Amit Varma]: it has to be a joke.

00:19:27.280 --> 00:19:33.240
[Amit Varma]: He would, he says, rather be treated unjustly than treat others unjustly.

00:19:33.240 --> 00:19:37.600
[Amit Varma]: But if areta is conceived of as analogous to the health of the body, then Socrates'

00:19:37.600 --> 00:19:39.720
[Amit Varma]: statement is hardly absurd.

00:19:39.720 --> 00:19:45.520
[Amit Varma]: The injustice that we do involves us far more intimately than the injustice that we suffer.

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:50.400
[Amit Varma]: I don't only act out of character, my character reacts to my actions.

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:51.400
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:52.400
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:59.760
[Guest]: And it becomes this, it gets transformed in the Socratic-Platonic attack on their own

00:19:59.760 --> 00:20:07.160
[Guest]: society's values into, yeah, it's something internal.

00:20:07.160 --> 00:20:08.280
[Guest]: It's not the applause.

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:09.280
[Guest]: It's not outer attention.

00:20:09.280 --> 00:20:12.880
[Guest]: In fact, you know, you may be getting no applause whatsoever.

00:20:12.880 --> 00:20:19.760
[Guest]: You may be getting a brooming cup of hemlock as Socrates got, you know, and yet it's this,

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:26.240
[Guest]: if your character is being transformed in the right direction, this, this is what, what

00:20:26.240 --> 00:20:27.240
[Guest]: counts.

00:20:27.240 --> 00:20:31.600
[Guest]: And, you know, and then the, the, the whole question becomes, well, what is the right

00:20:31.600 --> 00:20:32.600
[Guest]: direction?

00:20:32.600 --> 00:20:33.880
[Guest]: What are the virtues?

00:20:33.880 --> 00:20:34.880
[Guest]: How do we know?

00:20:34.880 --> 00:20:35.880
[Guest]: How do we judge?

00:20:35.880 --> 00:20:37.840
[Guest]: Uh, what are the right virtues?

00:20:37.840 --> 00:20:42.800
[Guest]: You know, which becomes, you know, a central theme of philosophy and what is really knowledge,

00:20:42.800 --> 00:20:45.800
[Guest]: you know, becomes a central theme of epistemology.

00:20:45.800 --> 00:20:54.920
[Guest]: So philosophy is often running with this transformation of, you know, from the, the attention and

00:20:54.920 --> 00:21:03.340
[Guest]: approbation of your fellow citizens to know that that's not a reliable means of judging

00:21:03.340 --> 00:21:05.760
[Guest]: whether you're living your life as you ought to live it.

00:21:05.760 --> 00:21:10.720
[Guest]: And in fact, it's something far more private, something that takes a tremendous amount of

00:21:10.720 --> 00:21:15.480
[Guest]: striving, but not striving just to be replicated in other people's minds.

00:21:15.480 --> 00:21:22.440
[Guest]: In fact, you may be in the eyes of your fellow citizens, a nobody, a failure, a loser, um,

00:21:22.440 --> 00:21:27.720
[Guest]: to use one of the favorite phrases of our current president of the United States, you

00:21:27.720 --> 00:21:28.720
[Amit Varma]: know, loser.

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:29.720
[Unknown]: Everybody's a loser.

00:21:29.720 --> 00:21:30.720
[Unknown]: Sad.

00:21:30.720 --> 00:21:31.720
[Unknown]: Sad.

00:21:31.720 --> 00:21:36.520
[Guest]: Um, you know, and, uh, yeah, so, you know, this is a very good example.

00:21:36.520 --> 00:21:42.360
[Guest]: I mean, I somehow, you know, being American, everything nowadays comes back to Trump, right?

00:21:42.360 --> 00:21:45.840
[Guest]: He colonizes our minds in a terrible way.

00:21:45.840 --> 00:21:53.560
[Guest]: But yet you look at this life, I mean, this is a person who is after, um, kleos, um, attention,

00:21:53.560 --> 00:21:55.680
[Guest]: outward attention in the biggest way possible.

00:21:55.680 --> 00:22:01.400
[Guest]: He has to be thought of by every citizen, every citizen on the globe, every human, and

00:22:01.400 --> 00:22:06.160
[Guest]: he is, um, is this a successful life by Greek standards?

00:22:06.160 --> 00:22:07.160
[Guest]: Yes.

00:22:07.160 --> 00:22:11.920
[Guest]: You know, by pre-philosophical, the Homeric ethos of the extraordinary, yes, he's an extraordinary

00:22:11.920 --> 00:22:12.920
[Guest]: person, right?

00:22:12.920 --> 00:22:14.920
[Guest]: He is replicated in all of our minds.

00:22:14.920 --> 00:22:18.800
[Guest]: Um, you know, what would Socrates and Plato have to say about him?

00:22:18.800 --> 00:22:22.240
[Guest]: We know what Socrates and Plato would have to say about him.

00:22:22.240 --> 00:22:28.440
[Guest]: And the fact that so many of us would echo Socrates and Plato's opinion, um, of, of,

00:22:28.440 --> 00:22:35.760
[Guest]: of this kind of kleos, this outward domination of the world consciousness shows how much,

00:22:35.760 --> 00:22:41.160
[Guest]: um, philosophy has in fact, uh, infiltrated, uh, our minds.

00:22:41.160 --> 00:22:46.520
[Guest]: This is one of the theme, you know, this, the, um, subtitle of this book is why philosophy

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:48.040
[Guest]: won't go away.

00:22:48.040 --> 00:22:52.080
[Guest]: And this is an ongoing argument I have in my background is in science.

00:22:52.080 --> 00:22:55.280
[Guest]: I come from a science, you know, from physics and mathematics.

00:22:55.280 --> 00:23:00.820
[Guest]: Um, most of my friends and all of my husbands have been themselves scientists.

00:23:00.820 --> 00:23:05.960
[Guest]: And so this question of, um, what is philosophy adding here?

00:23:05.960 --> 00:23:13.120
[Guest]: And it's very hard to see philosophical progress because it's the progress with which we see,

00:23:13.120 --> 00:23:18.760
[Guest]: you know, those of us who are judging a person like Trump to be, you know, a failure, he's

00:23:18.760 --> 00:23:23.800
[Guest]: calling everybody a loser, but that he's a loser himself in the true sense, in the biggest

00:23:23.800 --> 00:23:29.560
[Guest]: sense, a waste of the human life, um, and a waste of tremendous privilege and resources.

00:23:29.560 --> 00:23:31.960
[Guest]: Um, why are we doing this?

00:23:31.960 --> 00:23:38.400
[Guest]: I mean, this, this, this is a, a, a kind of progress that was begun with Socrates and

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:42.880
[Guest]: Plato's, uh, argument with those values of their own society.

00:23:42.880 --> 00:23:49.040
[Guest]: And that has, uh, you know, continued and infiltrated all of our, in fact, a very funny

00:23:49.040 --> 00:23:53.260
[Amit Varma]: illustration of this progress of philosophy in your book, where you have all these dialogues

00:23:53.260 --> 00:23:58.000
[Amit Varma]: with Plato in modern settings is when he's at the Googleplex and he's surprised to learn

00:23:58.000 --> 00:23:59.960
[Guest]: that slavery is no more.

00:23:59.960 --> 00:24:03.760
[Amit Varma]: He is charmed and beguiled by the arguments against slavery that the person who is with

00:24:03.760 --> 00:24:04.760
[Guest]: him gives him.

00:24:04.760 --> 00:24:05.760
[Guest]: Yes.

00:24:05.760 --> 00:24:09.320
[Guest]: And, and, and she, of course, you know, I made her, it's a little bit of comic relief,

00:24:09.320 --> 00:24:10.320
[Guest]: right?

00:24:10.320 --> 00:24:15.240
[Guest]: But she's the meteor escort when a writer is on a book tour, somebody meets them in

00:24:15.240 --> 00:24:18.800
[Guest]: each city and takes them around to all of their events.

00:24:18.800 --> 00:24:23.560
[Guest]: And um, and they, they tend to be usually, you know, very amusing people and, you know,

00:24:23.560 --> 00:24:26.920
[Guest]: charming, but you know, not, not intellectuals really.

00:24:26.920 --> 00:24:31.840
[Guest]: And I, so my media escort in this kind of telling how this very flaky kind of person

00:24:31.840 --> 00:24:36.440
[Amit Varma]: is actually giving such a solid philosophical argument, which has come from Plato himself

00:24:36.440 --> 00:24:40.760
[Guest]: in some sense, because how does philosophy make progress?

00:24:40.760 --> 00:24:47.840
[Guest]: We don't make progress in terms of, um, experiments or, you know, laboratory empirical, it's not

00:24:47.840 --> 00:24:50.240
[Guest]: an empirical science clearly.

00:24:50.240 --> 00:24:57.080
[Guest]: Um, but the way we make progress here is, you know, we, we keep seeing the implications

00:24:57.080 --> 00:25:01.520
[Guest]: of, um, commitments that we've already made and the strongest being commitments to our

00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:06.960
[Guest]: own life that we ourselves feel that we matter, or in any case we want to matter, it matters

00:25:06.960 --> 00:25:09.200
[Guest]: to us whether we matter.

00:25:09.200 --> 00:25:10.800
[Guest]: That is what it is to pursue a life.

00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:13.640
[Guest]: Your life has to matter to you in order just to pursue it.

00:25:13.640 --> 00:25:16.960
[Guest]: Um, what are the, what, what follows from this?

00:25:16.960 --> 00:25:22.320
[Guest]: And, and so many times we don't see what follows from this and we were inconsistent and that's

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:28.920
[Guest]: exactly how philosophy makes progress by looking at things that we've already committed ourselves

00:25:28.920 --> 00:25:34.360
[Guest]: to that we can't live our lives without committing ourselves to and seeing how we, how we are

00:25:34.360 --> 00:25:41.040
[Guest]: inconsistent, that this has consequences, logical consequences, and you know, we don't

00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:42.040
[Guest]: see them.

00:25:42.040 --> 00:25:48.320
[Guest]: And that's, in fact, this was this, uh, this is why the reductio ad absurdum, this form

00:25:48.320 --> 00:25:51.640
[Guest]: of argument was the favored form of Socrates, right?

00:25:51.640 --> 00:25:56.640
[Guest]: He developed this, you know, here you're committed to this, here are your premises, and yet you're

00:25:56.640 --> 00:25:57.640
[Guest]: not committed to this.

00:25:57.640 --> 00:25:58.640
[Guest]: Do you see the inconsistency?

00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:03.480
[Guest]: And he, he would point out to people their inconsistencies, which didn't win him great

00:26:03.480 --> 00:26:04.480
[Amit Varma]: popularity.

00:26:04.480 --> 00:26:08.960
[Amit Varma]: And it didn't work out well for the poor guy and, and part of the reason why it didn't

00:26:08.960 --> 00:26:14.200
[Amit Varma]: work out well for him is because the Athenian sense of Aretha was tied up with the state.

00:26:14.200 --> 00:26:16.400
[Amit Varma]: You had to have the validation of the state.

00:26:16.400 --> 00:26:20.760
[Amit Varma]: And there's another quote, which, you know, if you replace Athenian with say American,

00:26:20.760 --> 00:26:23.080
[Amit Varma]: the court might still make sense.

00:26:23.080 --> 00:26:28.320
[Amit Varma]: Start quote, Athenian superiority drew itself to more superiority, intensifying its sense

00:26:28.320 --> 00:26:33.120
[Amit Varma]: of his own exceptionalism, which typically happens with imperial powers.

00:26:33.120 --> 00:26:34.120
[Guest]: Stop quote.

00:26:34.120 --> 00:26:35.120
[Guest]: Yes, exactly.

00:26:35.120 --> 00:26:36.120
[Guest]: Yes.

00:26:36.120 --> 00:26:41.760
[Guest]: And so, you know, it was a great, if you have a society whose, whose normative framework

00:26:41.760 --> 00:26:43.960
[Guest]: is built on, you know, everybody has to be exceptional.

00:26:43.960 --> 00:26:49.240
[Guest]: Well, the big problem is, of course, most of us are not exceptional, right?

00:26:49.240 --> 00:26:54.640
[Guest]: We're perfectly, but yes, I mean, by definition, we're ordinary, most of us.

00:26:54.640 --> 00:26:56.680
[Guest]: And so what, you know, what did you do?

00:26:56.680 --> 00:27:00.760
[Guest]: Well, you, I call it participatory exceptionalism.

00:27:00.760 --> 00:27:08.600
[Guest]: You know, you're participating in an exceptional city state and of course, Athens was the most,

00:27:08.600 --> 00:27:15.640
[Guest]: it was a given premise, a firm premise among all of the ancient Greeks of no matter what

00:27:15.640 --> 00:27:19.040
[Guest]: city state that they were the best in the world, right?

00:27:19.040 --> 00:27:21.880
[Guest]: This comes very naturally to our species.

00:27:21.880 --> 00:27:28.040
[Guest]: And you know, in fact, their word for a foreigner is barbarian because, and it comes from their

00:27:28.040 --> 00:27:32.400
[Guest]: word for blah, blah, blah, what, you know, just is bar, bar, bar, you know, you can't

00:27:32.400 --> 00:27:34.360
[Guest]: understand what they're saying.

00:27:34.360 --> 00:27:36.200
[Guest]: So they're barbarians, right?

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:39.720
[Guest]: And it simply meant not Greek speakers.

00:27:39.720 --> 00:27:47.520
[Guest]: And so, but there was that, that kind of implication, lesser, there are lesser people.

00:27:47.520 --> 00:27:54.200
[Guest]: And then among these exceptional Greek speakers, the most exceptional, the creme de la creme

00:27:54.200 --> 00:27:55.480
[Guest]: were the Athenians, right?

00:27:55.480 --> 00:27:58.000
[Guest]: And it was, it was an imperial power.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:02.640
[Guest]: They were an imperialist over their fellow Greek city states.

00:28:02.640 --> 00:28:09.880
[Guest]: And they were also a great draw for their, for all of the most creative people.

00:28:09.880 --> 00:28:15.320
[Guest]: So you know, Aristotle was not born in Athens, he came to Athens, he came to Athens to study

00:28:15.320 --> 00:28:23.040
[Guest]: in Plato's Academy, the first European university that was founded by Plato.

00:28:23.040 --> 00:28:30.640
[Guest]: And so there was this, this sense that the way you can achieve something big and extraordinary

00:28:30.640 --> 00:28:33.680
[Guest]: is by being a citizen of an extraordinary state.

00:28:33.680 --> 00:28:44.080
[Guest]: So there's this nationalist fervor that is so strong because the whole existential longing

00:28:44.080 --> 00:28:48.040
[Guest]: to make something of your life was tied, tied up in this.

00:28:48.040 --> 00:28:53.040
[Guest]: And this is a way, of course, that we all, it's a way we all try to do it, by the group

00:28:53.040 --> 00:28:57.640
[Guest]: we belong to, you know, that this is a way of, rather than the values that we cultivate

00:28:57.640 --> 00:29:00.800
[Guest]: within our soul, the group that we belong to.

00:29:00.800 --> 00:29:05.480
[Amit Varma]: And where Plato, Socrates kind of moved away from this was by saying that it was in a sense

00:29:05.480 --> 00:29:11.000
[Amit Varma]: by rejecting the Athenian notion of arete, and saying that virtue comes not from belonging

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:13.640
[Amit Varma]: to an exceptional state, but from knowledge.

00:29:13.640 --> 00:29:19.760
[Amit Varma]: And I found it very fascinating where you talk about the sublime braid, which is the

00:29:19.760 --> 00:29:26.080
[Amit Varma]: connection between truth and beauty and virtue, and the notion that from knowledge arises

00:29:26.080 --> 00:29:27.080
[Amit Varma]: virtue.

00:29:27.080 --> 00:29:28.480
[Amit Varma]: Can you explain that to me?

00:29:28.480 --> 00:29:36.960
[Guest]: So it's, yeah, the truth, beauty and goodness are entwined with each other.

00:29:36.960 --> 00:29:39.320
[Guest]: This is so fundamental in Plato.

00:29:39.320 --> 00:29:44.760
[Guest]: One of the reasons I like Plato, although I do not think that everything he said was

00:29:44.760 --> 00:29:47.160
[Guest]: right, clearly not right.

00:29:47.160 --> 00:29:51.680
[Guest]: But again, how could I think that philosophy makes progress and think that everything Plato

00:29:51.680 --> 00:29:52.680
[Guest]: said was right?

00:29:52.680 --> 00:29:56.440
[Guest]: No, we can, we've made so much progress, we can look back at Plato and say, no, you were

00:29:56.440 --> 00:30:01.600
[Guest]: wrong about this, this and this, and many other things.

00:30:01.600 --> 00:30:08.640
[Guest]: But something that's very fundamental about him, he changed his mind many times.

00:30:08.640 --> 00:30:16.320
[Guest]: And this discipline that he really founded for us is a very self-critical, it's reason,

00:30:16.320 --> 00:30:19.520
[Guest]: but everything is open to reason.

00:30:19.520 --> 00:30:22.680
[Guest]: Everything has to be justified.

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:29.200
[Guest]: And so there's a great self-critical capacity that has to be cultivated in order to be a

00:30:29.200 --> 00:30:30.200
[Guest]: philosopher.

00:30:30.200 --> 00:30:35.160
[Guest]: I feel that any philosopher who hasn't changed her mind many times over the course of her

00:30:35.160 --> 00:30:43.600
[Guest]: life is really not being a good philosopher because this is critical, this self-criticism.

00:30:43.600 --> 00:30:49.480
[Guest]: So but one of the things that stays permanent with him is that, what I call the sublime

00:30:49.480 --> 00:30:58.160
[Guest]: grade, the intertwining of these three most important things for him, truth and beauty

00:30:58.160 --> 00:31:05.640
[Guest]: and goodness, and that they all are connected, they're embedded with each other.

00:31:05.640 --> 00:31:09.600
[Guest]: You can't achieve any one without the other.

00:31:09.600 --> 00:31:14.920
[Guest]: So for example, how can we tell that something is true?

00:31:14.920 --> 00:31:19.480
[Guest]: There has to be a beautiful explanation.

00:31:19.480 --> 00:31:27.680
[Guest]: So if we have, you know, two or more explanations that are, that can accommodate all of the

00:31:27.680 --> 00:31:32.440
[Guest]: things that we're trying to explain, all of the evidence, we go with the most beautiful

00:31:32.440 --> 00:31:36.520
[Guest]: one, the most elegant one, in some sense the simplest one.

00:31:36.520 --> 00:31:44.280
[Guest]: But there's an aesthetic evaluation of that as a criterion for truth.

00:31:44.280 --> 00:31:51.920
[Guest]: Now, I come from a background in physics and that is very, very apparent in physics.

00:31:51.920 --> 00:32:00.560
[Guest]: You know that when we, for example, turned away from the geocentric view, that the heavens

00:32:00.560 --> 00:32:05.560
[Guest]: all revolved around the earth and moved the Copernican Revolution to the heliocentric

00:32:05.560 --> 00:32:12.640
[Guest]: universe, both systems could accommodate all of the empirical evidence, the movements of

00:32:12.640 --> 00:32:16.840
[Guest]: the planets and all of this, but one of them was really messy.

00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:19.600
[Guest]: You had to keep adding more and more epicycles.

00:32:19.600 --> 00:32:27.400
[Guest]: It was mathematically grotesque, right, and one, all you had to do was change the orientation

00:32:27.400 --> 00:32:34.000
[Guest]: and make the sun the center with the earth moving and the, everything became, the explanation

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:37.240
[Guest]: itself became beautiful, became mathematically simple.

00:32:37.240 --> 00:32:42.400
[Guest]: We still, this is still the case, you know, so for, you know, all the way, you know, with

00:32:42.400 --> 00:32:48.480
[Guest]: relativity theory, when Einstein proposed the general theory of relativity, he had very

00:32:48.480 --> 00:32:51.560
[Guest]: little empirical evidence for it.

00:32:51.560 --> 00:32:57.880
[Guest]: What he had was beautiful mathematics, the mathematics is stunning, the theory itself

00:32:57.880 --> 00:33:05.320
[Guest]: is stunning and when it, it, it, he was proposed, the general theory was published in 1915,

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:09.360
[Guest]: had to wait until 1919 until he had any empirical evidence for it.

00:33:09.360 --> 00:33:15.360
[Guest]: They needed a complete eclipse, a solar eclipse so that they could see whether or not, I won't,

00:33:15.360 --> 00:33:16.360
[Guest]: I won't go into it.

00:33:16.360 --> 00:33:20.960
[Amit Varma]: I, I, I get that connection between truth and beauty, that a certain truth about the

00:33:20.960 --> 00:33:25.720
[Amit Varma]: universe is expressed beautifully by E is equal to MC squared, say, but how does knowing

00:33:25.720 --> 00:33:27.600
[Guest]: that translate to virtue?

00:33:27.600 --> 00:33:28.600
[Guest]: To virtue.

00:33:28.600 --> 00:33:32.000
[Guest]: So here is what Plato believed.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:41.680
[Guest]: He believed that if we really assimilate truth, which takes, first of all, that itself takes

00:33:41.680 --> 00:33:43.400
[Guest]: virtue.

00:33:43.400 --> 00:33:46.800
[Guest]: It takes taming of the ego, right?

00:33:46.800 --> 00:33:55.000
[Guest]: Because we have a great tendency to believe what's true, what, if it most flatters ourselves,

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:59.160
[Guest]: our place in society, our place in the universe, I mean, why did we think that the earth had

00:33:59.160 --> 00:34:02.520
[Guest]: to be the center of the universe with all the heavens revolving around us, right?

00:34:02.520 --> 00:34:08.560
[Guest]: It flatters our, our sense of importance in the cosmos, you know, so just to be able to

00:34:08.560 --> 00:34:14.400
[Guest]: attain the truth means you have to subdue the ego somewhat, right?

00:34:14.400 --> 00:34:22.840
[Guest]: But that also, when we see the truth, our perspective is so broadened.

00:34:22.840 --> 00:34:32.320
[Guest]: We see ourselves in this greatest perspective, the grandest perspective, and that itself,

00:34:32.320 --> 00:34:39.320
[Guest]: you know, expands our virtue, gives us a tolerance, and we don't take ourselves so damn seriously,

00:34:39.320 --> 00:34:40.320
[Guest]: right?

00:34:40.320 --> 00:34:45.760
[Guest]: I mean, this is, this is the aim of ethics to, we see ourselves in some perspectives

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:52.000
[Guest]: in regard with other, of our fellow citizens and fellow creatures and our planet itself,

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:55.000
[Guest]: our cosmos itself.

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:56.640
[Guest]: This is what it is to be virtuous.

00:34:56.640 --> 00:35:02.000
[Guest]: So yeah, so that's how these things all become intertwined.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:05.640
[Guest]: I just wanted to say this, this one thing that Einstein had said when he finally was

00:35:05.640 --> 00:35:13.680
[Guest]: brought the evidence for the general theory of relativity, that yes, light, the mass of,

00:35:13.680 --> 00:35:18.040
[Guest]: the mass of the sun actually did shift light in the way that he had predicted, and it was

00:35:18.040 --> 00:35:20.120
[Guest]: a huge, you know, success for this theory.

00:35:20.120 --> 00:35:25.140
[Guest]: And so a philosopher of science, Hans-Reichenbach, asked him, how did you feel when you finally

00:35:25.140 --> 00:35:29.920
[Guest]: got news that your theory had been vindicated?

00:35:29.920 --> 00:35:34.520
[Guest]: And he said, oh, no, I already knew it had to be true because it's so beautiful.

00:35:34.520 --> 00:35:37.800
[Guest]: So the empirical evidence just didn't even matter so much.

00:35:37.800 --> 00:35:41.600
[Guest]: So you know, this, and this we can trace all the way back to Plato.

