[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

00:36:55.840 --> 00:37:00.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, one of the most revelatory points while reading your book was that way back

00:37:00.520 --> 00:37:06.880
[Amit Varma]: then, when all the other normative religions were sort of taking root, you had Socrates

00:37:06.880 --> 00:37:12.000
[Amit Varma]: basically demolishing the notion of God by asking Yutipro, I hope I'm pronouncing that

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:13.000
[Guest]: right.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:14.000
[Guest]: Yutipro.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:15.000
[Amit Varma]: Yutipro.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:19.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, this fantastic question where he says, quote, is what is holy, holy because the gods

00:37:19.240 --> 00:37:20.280
[Amit Varma]: approve it?

00:37:20.280 --> 00:37:22.320
[Amit Varma]: Or do they approve it because it's holy?

00:37:22.320 --> 00:37:26.160
[Guest]: Yeah, this is fantastic.

00:37:26.160 --> 00:37:29.400
[Guest]: It's one of Plato's early dialogues.

00:37:29.400 --> 00:37:34.680
[Guest]: And the argument that Socrates puts forth there, or that Plato has Socrates putting

00:37:34.680 --> 00:37:42.240
[Guest]: forth there, has been repeated by freethinkers throughout the ages.

00:37:42.240 --> 00:37:47.920
[Guest]: You know, Spinoza, who's a great favorite philosopher of mine, the 17th century Jewish

00:37:47.920 --> 00:37:54.680
[Guest]: rationalist philosopher, very much following in the footsteps of Plato, you know, it's

00:37:54.680 --> 00:37:55.920
[Guest]: repeated by him.

00:37:55.920 --> 00:38:00.960
[Guest]: And in our own day, Sam Harris, you know, repeats this argument and people don't always

00:38:00.960 --> 00:38:07.360
[Guest]: attribute it to Plato, but he's the one who first formulated this extremely elegant argument.

00:38:07.360 --> 00:38:11.600
[Amit Varma]: Just for the listeners, I'll kind of quickly explain what it's essentially saying is that

00:38:11.600 --> 00:38:18.040
[Amit Varma]: if there are normative moral codes that you follow because God tells you to follow it,

00:38:18.040 --> 00:38:22.280
[Amit Varma]: are you doing that because he, like, is he telling you to do good things because there

00:38:22.280 --> 00:38:26.920
[Amit Varma]: is a reason for those to be good, in which case those reasons are enough in themselves.

00:38:26.920 --> 00:38:27.920
[Guest]: You don't need the God.

00:38:27.920 --> 00:38:28.920
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:38:28.920 --> 00:38:31.120
[Guest]: And if there are no reasons, then why do it?

00:38:31.120 --> 00:38:32.120
[Guest]: And why do it?

00:38:32.120 --> 00:38:37.520
[Guest]: I mean, if it's simply a caprice of God, you know, a whim, you know, do this, you know,

00:38:37.520 --> 00:38:45.880
[Guest]: give charity to the widow and to the orphan rather than, you know, persecute them.

00:38:45.880 --> 00:38:51.440
[Guest]: There's no additional reason that dictates this moral choice.

00:38:51.440 --> 00:38:56.280
[Guest]: Does that really answer the question we're asking when we want to know what makes good

00:38:56.280 --> 00:38:57.360
[Guest]: actions good?

00:38:57.360 --> 00:39:00.200
[Guest]: What makes evil evil?

00:39:00.200 --> 00:39:03.640
[Guest]: Just the whims and caprices of an immoral God.

00:39:03.640 --> 00:39:06.680
[Guest]: So no, we feel not, you know, we feel no.

00:39:06.680 --> 00:39:10.360
[Guest]: There's a reason God wants us to do this rather than that.

00:39:10.360 --> 00:39:14.520
[Guest]: Well, then if there's the reason, that's the reason, and God is redundant.

00:39:14.520 --> 00:39:18.640
[Guest]: It's a very elegant argument.

00:39:18.640 --> 00:39:25.800
[Guest]: And you know, I think sometimes it's against my will in certain debates with theists who

00:39:25.800 --> 00:39:30.240
[Guest]: want to argue there can't be no morality without God.

00:39:30.240 --> 00:39:34.320
[Guest]: And you know, this is an argument that I have had to face so many times.

00:39:34.320 --> 00:39:40.680
[Guest]: And you know, you give them, for me, the best response is Plato's argument, you know, 2400

00:39:40.680 --> 00:39:48.240
[Guest]: years ago, pre-Christian, pre-Jewish, you know, but that it's, yeah, it's a very, very

00:39:48.240 --> 00:39:49.560
[Amit Varma]: elegant argument.

00:39:49.560 --> 00:39:53.320
[Amit Varma]: And this brings me to my next question, which is really puzzling, which is that you have

00:39:53.320 --> 00:39:58.480
[Amit Varma]: this outbreak of what we would call rationality in this period where Socrates and Plato and

00:39:58.480 --> 00:40:00.680
[Amit Varma]: Aristotle are doing well.

00:40:00.680 --> 00:40:05.200
[Amit Varma]: And then you have this long sort of interval until the Enlightenment in the 18th century

00:40:05.200 --> 00:40:06.840
[Amit Varma]: before you have that.

00:40:06.840 --> 00:40:13.560
[Amit Varma]: And the rest of the time is all of those religions, those monotheistic cults, all of that thinking

00:40:13.560 --> 00:40:17.760
[Amit Varma]: you should have, you would think would go away with Plato's question, at least the rationalism

00:40:17.760 --> 00:40:19.280
[Amit Varma]: would survive.

00:40:19.280 --> 00:40:21.200
[Amit Varma]: But it disappears for several hundred years.

00:40:21.200 --> 00:40:22.200
[Guest]: Why is that?

00:40:22.200 --> 00:40:31.960
[Guest]: Well, you know, partly, you know, one of the problems with this religion of reason, you

00:40:31.960 --> 00:40:40.680
[Guest]: could almost call it, right, or a normativity of reason, is that it requires a lot of hard

00:40:40.680 --> 00:40:41.680
[Guest]: work.

00:40:41.680 --> 00:40:42.680
[Guest]: It requires education.

00:40:42.680 --> 00:40:48.880
[Guest]: You don't get the most comforting answers from it, right?

00:40:48.880 --> 00:40:50.880
[Guest]: You know, it depends on us.

00:40:50.880 --> 00:40:53.560
[Guest]: It's very human-centric.

00:40:53.560 --> 00:40:59.880
[Guest]: It makes the universe a kind of cold and uncaring place, an impersonal place.

00:40:59.880 --> 00:41:05.000
[Guest]: It's not surprising it broke out in ancient Greece, given what they thought of their gods,

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:08.720
[Guest]: which were, they're downright, you know, hostile to us.

00:41:08.720 --> 00:41:18.640
[Guest]: But it doesn't, whereas the, you know, the Judeo-Christian Muslim view, which captured

00:41:18.640 --> 00:41:21.800
[Guest]: the world, is that it's very powerful.

00:41:21.800 --> 00:41:23.800
[Guest]: It gives us a sense of cosmic significance.

00:41:23.800 --> 00:41:27.000
[Guest]: You know, I, myself, had started out that way.

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:29.680
[Guest]: I was born into an extremely religious family.

00:41:29.680 --> 00:41:34.800
[Guest]: I know what it feels like to make the transition of feeling, you know, that God is watching

00:41:34.800 --> 00:41:43.240
[Guest]: everything I do, which is terrifying because, I mean, it's really, there's no privacy whatsoever.

00:41:43.240 --> 00:41:45.360
[Guest]: And also, you know, he's a very stern God.

00:41:45.360 --> 00:41:49.880
[Guest]: He's judging if you do and, you know, in Judaism, which was my birth religion, it's, you know,

00:41:49.880 --> 00:41:54.960
[Guest]: there are laws for absolutely everything, laws specifically for women to keep them in

00:41:54.960 --> 00:41:56.400
[Guest]: their place.

00:41:56.400 --> 00:41:58.720
[Guest]: And these rankled me very much.

00:41:58.720 --> 00:42:02.800
[Guest]: These did not go down well with me.

00:42:02.800 --> 00:42:05.960
[Guest]: But one thing you never doubt, and that is that you matter.

00:42:05.960 --> 00:42:08.880
[Guest]: I mean, because you matter to the Lord of the universe.

00:42:08.880 --> 00:42:11.360
[Guest]: He created you intentionally.

00:42:11.360 --> 00:42:15.400
[Guest]: He has designed, you know, he created you rather than somebody else.

00:42:15.400 --> 00:42:17.520
[Guest]: So you have your place in the universe.

00:42:17.520 --> 00:42:24.000
[Guest]: You know, what I was saying about that village that, you know, that predates the axial age,

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:29.360
[Guest]: in some sense, it makes the universe a village, you know, that we all have, I've never thought

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:35.560
[Guest]: of that before, actually, but that we all have our place, you know, with the head chief,

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:37.440
[Guest]: you know, is there.

00:42:37.440 --> 00:42:38.440
[Guest]: And he had a really great...

00:42:38.440 --> 00:42:39.880
[Amit Varma]: Always a man.

00:42:39.880 --> 00:42:41.880
[Guest]: Always a man.

00:42:41.880 --> 00:42:45.640
[Guest]: And he had, you know, he has designs on us.

00:42:45.640 --> 00:42:52.720
[Guest]: And it's a comforting and it sort of replicates, you know, where we came from, that tribal

00:42:52.720 --> 00:42:54.360
[Guest]: village life.

00:42:54.360 --> 00:42:57.520
[Guest]: So it is our default, I think.

00:42:57.520 --> 00:43:00.920
[Guest]: And reason is pushing against that.

00:43:00.920 --> 00:43:09.920
[Guest]: And so I think it was such a powerful replication of the village intimacy, only on the cosmic

00:43:09.920 --> 00:43:13.040
[Guest]: scale that was presented to the world.

00:43:13.040 --> 00:43:14.040
[Guest]: It's not surprising.

00:43:14.040 --> 00:43:16.360
[Guest]: Also, it promises us an afterlife.

00:43:16.360 --> 00:43:22.800
[Guest]: I mean, it makes us extremely, you know, it assuages some of our deepest fears, which

00:43:22.800 --> 00:43:27.880
[Guest]: is that, you know, in the great scheme of things, we're really not so very much.

00:43:27.880 --> 00:43:30.640
[Guest]: No, we don't want to feel that.

00:43:30.640 --> 00:43:31.640
[Guest]: We fear death.

00:43:31.640 --> 00:43:32.640
[Guest]: All of these things.

00:43:32.640 --> 00:43:36.200
[Guest]: And it really palliates and speaks to our deepest fears.

00:43:36.200 --> 00:43:42.040
[Amit Varma]: One of the interesting points that you, the arguments that you address in the introduction

00:43:42.040 --> 00:43:47.640
[Amit Varma]: to your book, in fact, is about how people often say that philosophy, even today, is

00:43:47.640 --> 00:43:50.760
[Amit Varma]: just a set of footnotes to Plato, for example.

00:43:50.760 --> 00:43:55.120
[Amit Varma]: And people therefore make the argument, including I'm sure some of your scientist friends, that

00:43:55.120 --> 00:43:59.280
[Amit Varma]: science has progressed so much, you know, no one would say that science is like footnotes

00:43:59.280 --> 00:44:02.400
[Amit Varma]: to Pythagoras or whoever.

00:44:02.400 --> 00:44:06.560
[Amit Varma]: But with philosophy, we keep going back to Plato and finding it very relevant.

00:44:06.560 --> 00:44:09.480
[Amit Varma]: And you can actually begin an argument there.

00:44:09.480 --> 00:44:11.200
[Guest]: What do you have to say to that?

00:44:11.200 --> 00:44:12.200
[Guest]: Several things.

00:44:12.200 --> 00:44:16.320
[Guest]: I think that, you know, it was Alfred North Whitehead, a 20th century philosopher and

00:44:16.320 --> 00:44:20.040
[Guest]: logician who had said that the truest thing you can say about Western philosophy is that

00:44:20.040 --> 00:44:22.680
[Guest]: it consists of a series of footnotes to Plato.

00:44:22.680 --> 00:44:28.760
[Guest]: And this is a very good soundbite, but like most soundbites, it's a gross oversimplification.

00:44:28.760 --> 00:44:33.200
[Guest]: What you can say about Plato and the reason that he's so very important is that he had

00:44:33.200 --> 00:44:38.920
[Guest]: a real sense for what the philosophical questions were and what answers a philosophical question

00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:42.400
[Guest]: and what doesn't answer a philosophical question.

00:44:42.400 --> 00:44:47.120
[Guest]: And he found philosophical questions lurking in every area.

00:44:47.120 --> 00:44:51.720
[Guest]: So he lays out the landscape of philosophy, that we can say, the different areas, you

00:44:51.720 --> 00:44:55.560
[Guest]: know, philosophy of religion that we spoke about a little bit and, you know, and theory

00:44:55.560 --> 00:45:00.360
[Guest]: of knowledge, epistemology, moral philosophy, political philosophy, you know, all these

00:45:00.360 --> 00:45:04.680
[Guest]: different, but that there are always these philosophical questions that arise that are

00:45:04.680 --> 00:45:07.480
[Guest]: not one with the fields themselves.

00:45:07.480 --> 00:45:08.800
[Guest]: They're meta questions.

00:45:08.800 --> 00:45:11.960
[Guest]: They're about the philosophy of science, you know.

00:45:11.960 --> 00:45:18.440
[Guest]: So it's not that he laid out all of the answers, as I say, we can look back and see how many

00:45:18.440 --> 00:45:19.440
[Guest]: mistakes he made.

00:45:19.440 --> 00:45:20.640
[Guest]: I mean, his theory of forms.

00:45:20.640 --> 00:45:26.080
[Guest]: I don't know anybody who holds by this philosophy of language.

00:45:26.080 --> 00:45:29.800
[Guest]: He asked the important questions and he proposed his theory of form.

00:45:29.800 --> 00:45:30.800
[Guest]: What is a meaning?

00:45:30.800 --> 00:45:33.640
[Guest]: How does a word acquire meaning?

00:45:33.640 --> 00:45:35.680
[Guest]: And he had this theory of forms.

00:45:35.680 --> 00:45:40.000
[Guest]: We have philosophy of language now, very complicated, very sophisticated.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:41.280
[Guest]: It's not Platonic, right?

00:45:41.280 --> 00:45:46.400
[Guest]: It's not Plato's answers are not the answers, but Plato's questions, time and again, are

00:45:46.400 --> 00:45:47.400
[Guest]: the questions.

00:45:47.400 --> 00:45:50.800
[Guest]: But we've made, we've made progress with them.

00:45:50.800 --> 00:45:57.360
[Guest]: The other thing is the more scientific progress we make, the more philosophical questions

00:45:57.360 --> 00:46:01.480
[Guest]: are churned up by the scientific progress.

00:46:01.480 --> 00:46:06.680
[Amit Varma]: And so, you know, in fact, as you say, philosophy raises the proto-scientific questions that

00:46:06.680 --> 00:46:07.680
[Guest]: is, yes.

00:46:07.680 --> 00:46:15.960
[Guest]: So often philosophers will first ask the scientific question that kind of motivates the science

00:46:15.960 --> 00:46:21.120
[Guest]: and finally the methodology emerges that could, that could answer these questions.

00:46:21.120 --> 00:46:23.600
[Guest]: But that's not its only role.

00:46:23.600 --> 00:46:30.440
[Guest]: It also looks at what science, you know, the current science of the day is telling us and

00:46:30.440 --> 00:46:33.360
[Guest]: helps to determine what it's answering and what it's not answering.

00:46:33.360 --> 00:46:38.480
[Guest]: So for something like, for example, neuroscience.

00:46:38.480 --> 00:46:44.280
[Guest]: So we've learned so much more about consciousness, you know, through cognitive science and through

00:46:44.280 --> 00:46:50.000
[Guest]: neuroscience, we can map the brain and see where different aspects of consciousness,

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:51.000
[Guest]: where they're located.

00:46:51.000 --> 00:47:00.920
[Guest]: And, you know, I think neuroscience has made it extremely probable that consciousness is

00:47:00.920 --> 00:47:02.560
[Guest]: a brain process, right?

00:47:02.560 --> 00:47:07.880
[Guest]: That it's, it is, it is a material physical process.

00:47:07.880 --> 00:47:17.600
[Guest]: Has it thereby eliminated the notion of agency, that we're actually in control of our actions?

00:47:17.600 --> 00:47:23.280
[Guest]: Has it shown that we can possibly be free, that the sense that we have of actually making

00:47:23.280 --> 00:47:30.120
[Guest]: choices of, of just deliberating and deciding is an illusion.

00:47:30.120 --> 00:47:32.800
[Guest]: So this is a philosophical question.

00:47:32.800 --> 00:47:40.280
[Guest]: So look at what science has so far established and then see what it implies, what it doesn't

00:47:40.280 --> 00:47:41.280
[Guest]: imply.

00:47:41.280 --> 00:47:43.560
[Guest]: What's, what's still open.

00:47:43.560 --> 00:47:52.440
[Guest]: Scientists are often very eager to, to interpret their findings in the broadest way possible.

00:47:52.440 --> 00:47:57.440
[Guest]: So you'll find many neuroscientists, you know, I mean, we've answered all of these philosophical

00:47:57.440 --> 00:48:02.200
[Guest]: questions and that's where people trained in philosophy, you know, they have to look,

00:48:02.200 --> 00:48:04.640
[Guest]: know the science, be trained in the science.

00:48:04.640 --> 00:48:11.280
[Guest]: But as the philosophical question, does it really entail what the scientists are saying

00:48:11.280 --> 00:48:12.280
[Guest]: that it entails?

00:48:12.280 --> 00:48:19.600
[Guest]: I mean, in physics, which was the, the, the science, the scientific field that I'm most

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:26.240
[Guest]: interested in, that I had most studied in university, there is, you know, we have this

00:48:26.240 --> 00:48:32.920
[Guest]: very strange theory, quantum mechanics, and we don't quite know how to interpret it.

00:48:32.920 --> 00:48:40.840
[Guest]: And you know, when I was taking my physics courses, there was one view, you know, about

00:48:40.840 --> 00:48:48.040
[Guest]: quantum mechanics, which is, was associated with Niels Bohr, was called Copenhagen interpretation,

00:48:48.040 --> 00:48:51.480
[Guest]: which is that, you know, things don't exist until you measure them.

00:48:51.480 --> 00:48:56.240
[Guest]: So to ask where is the particle before it's measured, where, you know, where had it been

00:48:56.240 --> 00:48:58.120
[Guest]: before, is a meaningless question.

00:48:58.120 --> 00:49:02.480
[Guest]: You know, this is a philosophical view.

00:49:02.480 --> 00:49:08.240
[Guest]: And what happened was philosophers began to examine this view and say, look, here's quantum

00:49:08.240 --> 00:49:09.240
[Guest]: mechanics.

00:49:09.240 --> 00:49:10.480
[Guest]: Here's what you found.

00:49:10.480 --> 00:49:15.400
[Guest]: The interpretation of quantum mechanics, this is philosophical, is it good philosophy?

00:49:15.400 --> 00:49:21.520
[Guest]: And they're the ones who really prodded physicists so that they came up with other interpretations

00:49:21.520 --> 00:49:22.520
[Guest]: as well.

00:49:22.520 --> 00:49:23.680
[Guest]: There's the Bohmian interpretation.

00:49:23.680 --> 00:49:25.200
[Guest]: There's the multiverse interpretation.

00:49:25.200 --> 00:49:29.480
[Guest]: These things were first proposed by, by philosophical thinking.

00:49:29.480 --> 00:49:35.960
[Guest]: So this is another way in which the more progress we make with our science and getting into

00:49:35.960 --> 00:49:42.440
[Guest]: stranger and stranger things, to see what it implies and what it doesn't imply.

00:49:42.440 --> 00:49:46.160
[Guest]: And that, that is, that's the work I think very much of philosophy.

00:49:46.160 --> 00:49:56.240
[Guest]: What philosophy is after is to maximize our overall coherence, to see what we know and

00:49:56.240 --> 00:50:04.640
[Guest]: what other possibilities that leaves open, closes off, to try to make us as consistent

00:50:04.640 --> 00:50:05.640
[Guest]: and coherent.

00:50:05.640 --> 00:50:10.840
[Guest]: That has always been the role of philosophy ever since Socrates was wandering around asking

00:50:10.840 --> 00:50:13.440
[Guest]: his annoying questions of his fellow citizens.

00:50:13.440 --> 00:50:16.920
[Amit Varma]: And just speaking of those annoying questions and what the task of philosophy is, there's

00:50:16.920 --> 00:50:21.360
[Amit Varma]: another great passage from your book I'd like to quote, which is, quote, truth cannot be

00:50:21.360 --> 00:50:25.880
[Amit Varma]: transmitted from one mind to another, the pouring out of the full flask of a master

00:50:25.880 --> 00:50:28.640
[Amit Varma]: into the passive receptacle of a student.

00:50:28.640 --> 00:50:33.800
[Amit Varma]: Truth seeking comes from the violent activity of philosophy, a drama enacted deep in the

00:50:33.800 --> 00:50:39.000
[Amit Varma]: interior of each of us and which manages in its violence to deprive us of positions that

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:43.960
[Amit Varma]: may be so deeply and constitutively personal that we can't defend them to others.

00:50:43.960 --> 00:50:48.560
[Amit Varma]: This violent activity is personal, even as it leads one in an impersonal direction where

00:50:48.560 --> 00:50:52.080
[Amit Varma]: interpersonal agreement is possible.

00:50:52.080 --> 00:50:53.080
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:50:53.080 --> 00:50:57.560
[Amit Varma]: And this kind of also sort of describes the Socratic method of how he did his dialogues

00:50:57.560 --> 00:51:00.040
[Amit Varma]: and ask questions and got down to the essence of everything.

00:51:00.040 --> 00:51:05.640
[Amit Varma]: So my question to you is, would Socratic dialogue therefore be effective today in this polarized

00:51:05.640 --> 00:51:06.640
[Guest]: age?

00:51:06.640 --> 00:51:09.040
[Amit Varma]: Oh, I certainly, I certainly think so.

00:51:09.040 --> 00:51:11.440
[Amit Varma]: He would get torn apart on Twitter, for example.

00:51:11.440 --> 00:51:12.440
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:51:12.440 --> 00:51:13.440
[Guest]: Yes.

00:51:13.440 --> 00:51:14.440
[Guest]: He'd seem like a troll.

00:51:14.440 --> 00:51:15.440
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:51:15.440 --> 00:51:22.760
[Guest]: So, you know, yeah, one of the things that I think is very true of the philosophical

00:51:22.760 --> 00:51:26.880
[Guest]: enterprise is the dialogue is extremely important.

00:51:26.880 --> 00:51:28.880
[Guest]: You know, it began with the dialogue.

00:51:28.880 --> 00:51:32.160
[Guest]: Socrates never even wrote anything down because he believed in the lived conversation.

00:51:32.160 --> 00:51:38.520
[Guest]: It has to be minds clashing with other minds, and that's the way these deep intuitions that

00:51:38.520 --> 00:51:44.280
[Guest]: we don't even realize we have, because they're so deep down within us, that they can be brought

00:51:44.280 --> 00:51:48.520
[Guest]: to the floor and other people who don't share your intuitions will say, defend them, account

00:51:48.520 --> 00:51:51.320
[Guest]: for them, tell us why I ought to believe in them.

00:51:51.320 --> 00:51:55.040
[Guest]: And then, you know, sometimes you realize you really have no reason whatsoever.

00:51:55.040 --> 00:51:57.880
[Guest]: And that's how progress is made.

00:51:57.880 --> 00:52:01.280
[Guest]: One of the wonderful things that's happened in our own day is that, you know, more and

00:52:01.280 --> 00:52:03.640
[Guest]: more people are brought into this conversation.

00:52:03.640 --> 00:52:08.920
[Guest]: A person like me, a woman, would not have been part of this conversation for very long.

00:52:08.920 --> 00:52:12.360
[Guest]: And I have seen over the course of my lifetime how this has changed.

00:52:12.360 --> 00:52:15.680
[Guest]: When I entered into philosophy, I was the only woman in the room, especially because

00:52:15.680 --> 00:52:18.280
[Guest]: I did philosophy of science, philosophy of mathematics.

00:52:18.280 --> 00:52:21.920
[Guest]: These were really considered unfeminine, right, areas of philosophy.

00:52:21.920 --> 00:52:23.560
[Guest]: I was the only woman in the room.

00:52:23.560 --> 00:52:25.000
[Guest]: I'm not anymore, right?

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:26.080
[Guest]: There are many women.

00:52:26.080 --> 00:52:32.960
[Guest]: But this itself has brought philosophical questions into the conversation that were

00:52:32.960 --> 00:52:40.280
[Guest]: invisible to men, such as raising children, you know, questions about what is the right

00:52:40.280 --> 00:52:46.720
[Guest]: way, you know, children have been, care for the planet.

00:52:46.720 --> 00:52:54.320
[Guest]: I mean, the ecological concerns have become, you know, in general, for all of us, a very,

00:52:54.320 --> 00:53:00.960
[Guest]: very important part of philosophy, but more what we call applied ethics, rather than just

00:53:00.960 --> 00:53:06.600
[Guest]: grand theories of ethics, applied ethics, you know, really specific questions that are

00:53:06.600 --> 00:53:09.600
[Guest]: facing us have become much more prominent.

00:53:09.600 --> 00:53:13.280
[Amit Varma]: Like the trolley problem applied to autonomous cars, for example.

00:53:13.280 --> 00:53:21.960
[Guest]: Yes, yes, things of this sort that have, for some reason, you know, that women have found

00:53:21.960 --> 00:53:29.680
[Guest]: this, less grand theories and more applied ethics, you know, that are, you know, so ecology,

00:53:29.680 --> 00:53:36.600
[Guest]: family ethics, medical ethics, you find many, many women in medical ethics.

00:53:36.600 --> 00:53:43.680
[Guest]: So this is interesting to watch, and even the analogies that are, you know, we are always,

00:53:43.680 --> 00:53:48.880
[Guest]: one of the things that we do to test our intuitions is to do thought experiments, you know, and

00:53:48.880 --> 00:53:55.600
[Guest]: they're pretty wacky, often, the trolley problem seems to be an example of a thought experiment.

00:53:55.600 --> 00:54:00.360
[Guest]: The kinds of thought experiments that I hear now being proposed are often, you know, sort

00:54:00.360 --> 00:54:07.280
[Guest]: of coming from a woman's life, from a woman's perspective, a woman's sense of priorities,

00:54:07.280 --> 00:54:16.920
[Guest]: and so the wider the group that we bring in, people from different cultures, the better,

00:54:16.920 --> 00:54:21.240
[Guest]: because we come, the different cultures, the different life experiences give us such different

00:54:21.240 --> 00:54:24.320
[Guest]: intuitions that are invisible to the person.

00:54:24.320 --> 00:54:28.400
[Amit Varma]: But why I brought up the Socratic notion of dialogue in the modern age was, does it worry

00:54:28.400 --> 00:54:32.920
[Amit Varma]: you, for example, that in the last 10 years, what we've seen with social media and people

00:54:32.920 --> 00:54:37.520
[Amit Varma]: living so much of their lives online, is that people shut themselves off in echo chambers,

00:54:37.520 --> 00:54:42.480
[Amit Varma]: where they spend a lot of time posturing to raise their status within their in-group,

00:54:42.480 --> 00:54:45.240
[Amit Varma]: but don't really talk to each other, they just talk past each other.

00:54:45.240 --> 00:54:52.200
[Guest]: You know, when the World Wide Web, as we used to call it, was first proposed, this seemed

00:54:52.200 --> 00:54:58.280
[Guest]: the most liberating idea to a person like me, oh, now I can talk to people in India,

00:54:58.280 --> 00:55:04.440
[Guest]: I can talk to people in Afghanistan, and in Saudi Arabia, and I do, actually, talk to,

00:55:04.440 --> 00:55:05.440
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it can be used this way.

00:55:05.440 --> 00:55:07.440
[Amit Varma]: And the huge net benefit remains.

00:55:07.440 --> 00:55:12.640
[Guest]: Yes, but what we hadn't foreseen is what happened.

00:55:12.640 --> 00:55:20.600
[Guest]: Human nature, the worst of us, asserting itself in this new social media range.

00:55:20.600 --> 00:55:30.880
[Guest]: And so these echo chambers, and you only search out your own opinions that are so validated

00:55:30.880 --> 00:55:35.400
[Guest]: and strengthened, because everybody you're talking agrees with this.

00:55:35.400 --> 00:55:41.640
[Guest]: So, and this is, of course, the exact opposite of what the Socratic dialogue is supposed

00:55:41.640 --> 00:55:46.480
[Guest]: to be about, which is, again, I, myself, it's interesting, because psychologists have shown

00:55:46.480 --> 00:55:52.280
[Guest]: us that we, there's an endorphin lift, there's a kind of surge.

00:55:52.280 --> 00:55:58.360
[Guest]: When you hear your own opinions replicated in others, you feel good.

00:55:58.360 --> 00:55:59.360
[Guest]: And so...

00:55:59.360 --> 00:56:02.200
[Amit Varma]: So it's healthy to be in an echo chamber?

00:56:02.200 --> 00:56:05.720
[Guest]: Yes, it feels good.

00:56:05.720 --> 00:56:11.800
[Guest]: But you know, as soon as I read this, I started to read publications, you know, newspapers

00:56:11.800 --> 00:56:16.120
[Guest]: and periodicals that are, that I very much disagree with, right?

00:56:16.120 --> 00:56:22.240
[Guest]: And yes, I feel angry, you know, I don't feel, I don't feel comfortable reading these things.

00:56:22.240 --> 00:56:28.200
[Guest]: But I, you know, I force myself to, and I force myself to think out, well, what are

00:56:28.200 --> 00:56:31.600
[Guest]: they assuming that I'm not assuming?

00:56:31.600 --> 00:56:36.720
[Guest]: How do I defend my assumptions against their assumptions?

00:56:36.720 --> 00:56:38.360
[Guest]: It's a lot of work, right?

00:56:38.360 --> 00:56:42.080
[Guest]: This is a lot of work, but, and it's uncomfortable, and it doesn't feel so very good.

00:56:42.080 --> 00:56:47.720
[Guest]: But I think, I think that this is part of what it is to be an enlightened person.

00:56:47.720 --> 00:56:53.520
[Guest]: To be an enlightened person is to be aware of the things that you're assuming, and that

00:56:53.520 --> 00:56:57.680
[Guest]: they're not necessarily true to other people, and do you really have good reasons?

00:56:57.680 --> 00:56:59.000
[Guest]: Could you convince them?

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:03.040
[Guest]: What's the best that you could give them to try to change their minds?

00:57:03.040 --> 00:57:04.040
[Guest]: If we did that...

00:57:04.040 --> 00:57:07.040
[Amit Varma]: Are you generally hopeful that we're moving in the right direction?

00:57:07.040 --> 00:57:08.040
[Guest]: No.

00:57:08.040 --> 00:57:09.040
[Guest]: Oh, I don't know.

00:57:09.040 --> 00:57:10.040
[Guest]: Yes, maybe.

00:57:10.040 --> 00:57:11.040
[Guest]: I don't know.

00:57:11.040 --> 00:57:12.040
[Amit Varma]: I don't know.

00:57:12.040 --> 00:57:13.680
[Guest]: Okay, well, one, I've taken enough of your time.

00:57:13.680 --> 00:57:14.680
[Guest]: I know you've got to go.

00:57:14.680 --> 00:57:18.240
[Amit Varma]: So one, one kind of final question I've been waiting to ask, and you kind of alluded to

00:57:18.240 --> 00:57:20.920
[Amit Varma]: it a while back.

00:57:20.920 --> 00:57:22.780
[Amit Varma]: Do you believe in free will?

00:57:22.780 --> 00:57:27.800
[Amit Varma]: Because when you talk about virtue coming from knowledge, if you have complete knowledge,

00:57:27.800 --> 00:57:31.160
[Amit Varma]: doesn't that then make philosophy meaningless and virtue moot?

00:57:31.160 --> 00:57:34.960
[Guest]: Oh, that's a deep, it's a deep question.

00:57:34.960 --> 00:57:42.600
[Guest]: You know, I believe in, you know, to believe that we have this ability to look at our own

00:57:42.600 --> 00:57:52.600
[Guest]: thought processes and be self-critical about them and change our mind about them, without

00:57:52.600 --> 00:57:59.400
[Guest]: believing in that degree of freedom, you know, we can't make any sense out of what it is

00:57:59.400 --> 00:58:00.760
[Guest]: to be rational.

00:58:00.760 --> 00:58:06.920
[Guest]: So if we're committed to reason, we have to be committed to some degree of freedom.

00:58:06.920 --> 00:58:09.720
[Amit Varma]: To at least the illusion of free will.

00:58:09.720 --> 00:58:10.720
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah.

00:58:10.720 --> 00:58:13.360
[Guest]: No, I think we have to be even more.

00:58:13.360 --> 00:58:19.720
[Guest]: It's like, to say that there really is, you know, rational behavior, rational beliefs

00:58:19.720 --> 00:58:25.080
[Guest]: justify belief, and those which are irrational and unjustified, and that therefore ought

00:58:25.080 --> 00:58:26.560
[Guest]: not to be believed, right?

00:58:26.560 --> 00:58:35.720
[Guest]: There is a normative presupposition that is enfolded in epistemology itself.

00:58:35.720 --> 00:58:39.800
[Guest]: To be committed to that, we have to be committed to some degree of freedom.

00:58:39.800 --> 00:58:44.960
[Guest]: When I see, when I examine my own thought processes, because you come at me with these

00:58:44.960 --> 00:58:49.000
[Guest]: trenchant questions, and I say, well, I really don't know how to answer them.

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:54.040
[Guest]: I better go back to the drawing board and rethink it, and maybe I will, I will change

00:58:54.040 --> 00:58:55.040
[Guest]: my mind.

00:58:55.040 --> 00:58:59.080
[Guest]: That is, that's a presumption of being a reasonable person at all.

00:58:59.080 --> 00:59:07.180
[Guest]: So if, you know, what we have learned undermines reason itself, then we have no reason to even

00:59:07.180 --> 00:59:10.120
[Guest]: trust what we have learned, right?

00:59:10.120 --> 00:59:12.960
[Guest]: It's a, it's a kind of Pyrrhic victory.

00:59:12.960 --> 00:59:19.680
[Guest]: It will, it will destroy any claims we have to, to truth, to knowledge, to reason.

00:59:19.680 --> 00:59:25.640
[Guest]: So to that degree, I think we have to, we have to countenance free will.

